The paper deals with communication over a classical-quantum broadcast channel, which is a topic in information theory (cs.IT) and quantum information (cs.QI). The paper also involves the use of random codebook argument and mutual covering argument, which are techniques commonly used in coding theory (cs.CC) and cryptography (cs.CR). Additionally, the paper discusses smooth Renyi divergences, which are a measure of information similarity and are relevant to information theory and statistics (cs.SI).
